==== How to Compile and Run ====

  bash build.sh
  ./build/hw11

The build script runs CMake + make. The executable runs unit tests followed
by the LRU vs Random policy comparison.

==== Implementation Notes ====

Cache geometry:
  L1 Instruction: 512 sets, 1-way (direct-mapped), 64-byte lines
  L1 Data:        256 sets, 2-way set-associative, 64-byte lines
  L2:            8192 sets, 4-way set-associative, 64-byte lines

Address layout (MSB→LSB): tag | index | offset (6 offset bits).

Policy: write-back, write-allocate. L2 is inclusive of L1: on any L2
eviction the corresponding L1i and L1d lines are invalidated. If an L1
line is dirty at invalidation time it is written directly to memory (since
the L2 line is being discarded). Dirty L1 evictions to L2 count as L2
accesses in the stats.

L1 cache coherency: before any L1i read or write, any dirty L1d copy of
the same line is flushed to L2 (and vice-versa), so the other L1 always
reads the latest data from L2.

==== Testing Methodology: LRU vs Random Replacement ====

Four access patterns were used to compare the two policies:

1. Sequential Scan (1 MB)
   Reads 1 MB of memory linearly. Every cache line is accessed exactly
   once so no reuse is possible. Both policies produce identical miss
   counts (16,384 L1d misses, 16,384 L2 misses) because the replacement
   decision never matters when there is no temporal locality.

2. Strided Access (4 KB stride, 10,000 accesses)
   Accesses memory with a 4 KB stride, cycling through the 16 MB address
   space. Each access maps to a different L1d set, so nearly every access
   is an L1d miss regardless of policy. Both policies again perform
   similarly (~10,000 L1d misses each) since the working set never
   re-enters the cache.

3. Working-Set Loop (128 KB working set, 8 passes)
   Repeatedly scans a 128 KB region (4× the 32 KB L1d capacity) in
   cache-line-sized steps for 8 passes. The first pass cold-misses all
   2,048 L2 lines. On subsequent passes, LRU evicts lines in strict FIFO
   order causing every access after pass 1 to miss in L1d (16,384 total
   misses). Random eviction occasionally keeps a useful line alive,
   producing slightly fewer L1d misses (~16,269) while L2 miss counts
   remain equal at 2,048 — the working set fits in L2 regardless.

4. L1d Thrash (5-way conflict into a 2-way cache, 2,000 rounds)
   Repeatedly accesses 5 addresses that all map to the same L1d set,
   which can only hold 2 lines. LRU deterministically evicts the line
   that will be needed next, producing a miss on every single access after
   the first two cold loads (10,000 misses for 2,000 × 5 accesses).
   Random policy sometimes keeps the right line, lowering misses to ~9,342.
   This is the pattern where Random outperforms LRU most clearly.

Summary of Results:
  - Sequential / strided workloads: LRU ≈ Random (no reuse to exploit).
  - Working-set loop: Random marginally better in L1d.
  - Conflict thrash: Random noticeably better (~6% fewer L1d misses)
    because LRU degenerates into a worst-case cyclic eviction pattern
    while Random escapes it probabilistically.

In general, LRU is optimal for workloads with strong temporal locality
(recently-used lines are likely to be reused). Random performs comparably
or slightly better on adversarial conflict patterns where LRU's determinism
becomes a liability, and it has the advantage of constant-time selection
with no per-way metadata overhead.
